<a name="0">[0]</a> <a href="#0" id=0>These data models can also represent data lineage and other metadata by including narrative text, data definitions, and data tables within the file.</a>
<a name="1">[1]</a> <a href="#1" id=1>Each standard allows easy data interchange among scientists.</a>
<a name="2">[2]</a> <a href="#2" id=2>Simple and convenient data models have evolved to represent arrays and relationships among them.</a>
<a name="3">[3]</a> <a href="#3" id=3>Much science data is in the form of numeric arrays generated by instruments and simulations.</a>
<a name="4">[4]</a> <a href="#4" id=4>Data interchange outside each group is problematic.</a>
<a name="5">[5]</a> <a href="#5" id=5>While the commercial world has standardized on the relational data model and SQL, no single standard or tool has critical mass in the scientific community.</a>
<a name="6">[6]</a> <a href="#6" id=6>Definitions of common terminology (units and measurements) are emerging within each discipline.</a>
